.SH OPTIONS
.PP
\f[B]aaruremote\f[R] takes no options.
.SH DEVICE URI
.PP
From an Aaru client instance, devices exposed by \f[B]aaruremote\f[R]
are accessed using the following URI scheme:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
aaru://<IP_ADDRESS>/<DEVICE_PATH>
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
For example:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
aaru://192.168.1.10/dev/sda
\f[R]
.fi
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Start the server (as root):
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
sudo aaruremote
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
From Aaru, list the devices available on the remote machine:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
aaru list-devices aaru://192.168.1.10
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Test the connection using the Aaru remote command:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
aaru remote aaru://192.168.1.10
\f[R]
.fi
.SH PROTOCOL
.PP
\f[B]aaruremote\f[R] communicates over a proprietary binary protocol on
TCP port \f[B]6666\f[R].
Each message begins with an \f[B]AaruPacketHeader\f[R] containing a
magic identifier (\f[V]DICR\f[R]), a packet identifier (\f[V]PCKT\f[R]),
the message length, the protocol version, and the command type.
.PP
The maximum supported protocol version is \f[B]2\f[R].
.SH SYSTEMD SERVICE
.PP
A systemd service unit is provided to run \f[B]aaruremote\f[R]
automatically at boot.
.PP
To enable and start the service:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
systemctl enable aaruremote
systemctl start aaruremote
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
To check its status:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
systemctl status aaruremote
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
The service runs under the dedicated \f[B]aaruremote\f[R] user (group
\f[B]operator\f[R]), with supplementary groups \f[B]disk\f[R] and
\f[B]cdrom\f[R] to allow device access without root privileges.
It restarts automatically on failure.
.PP
Log output is appended to \f[B]/var/log/aaruremote.log\f[R].
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]/etc/systemd/system/aaruremote.service\f[R]
systemd unit file for the aaruremote daemon.
.TP
\f[B]/var/log/aaruremote.log\f[R]
Log file for standard output and error when running as a systemd
service.
.SH SEE ALSO
.PP
